1
00:00:00,160 --> 00:00:03,679
My name is Ben and I turned my side project into a full-time job.

2
00:00:03,679 --> 00:00:09,120
>> This is Ben, a regular dude in a regular 9 to-5 who always wanted to start his own business.

3
00:00:09,120 --> 00:00:16,160
He was always starting different side projects, but nothing really worked until one day he changed his entire approach.

4
00:00:16,160 --> 00:00:18,880
>> Don't go full-time on your project until you do this.

5
00:00:18,880 --> 00:00:26,720
>> Once he made this change, he started a business that would eventually hit 15,000 MR and allow him to work full-time on his own stuff.

6
00:00:26,720 --> 00:00:32,880
The idea finally started to get traction when I brought Ben onto the channel to share everything,

7
00:00:32,880 --> 00:00:39,600
including what he learned from all his failed side project ideas, why this idea was different,

8
00:00:39,600 --> 00:00:44,559
and how with the right approach, anybody can build a side project that makes money.

9
00:00:44,559 --> 00:00:46,160
All right, let's get into it.

10
00:00:46,160 --> 00:00:51,120
I'm Pat Walls and this is Starter Story.

11
00:00:51,120 --> 00:00:53,280
All right, welcome Ben to Starter Story.

12
00:00:53,280 --> 00:00:56,559
Tell me about who you are, what you built, and what's your story.

13
00:00:56,559 --> 00:01:00,800
>> My name is Ben Boz and I'm a software developer who created Tech Lockdown.

14
00:01:00,800 --> 00:01:08,320
Tech Lockdown is a platform that helps adults block websites and apps and just be more intentional with their internet use.

15
00:01:08,320 --> 00:01:19,840
It started out as a side project, but I was actually laid off in 2023, and I had to make the decision to either go full-time on my side project or accept a job offer and go back into working full-time.

16
00:01:19,840 --> 00:01:20,159
>> All right.

17
00:01:20,159 --> 00:01:23,360
Well, let's go a little bit deeper into how Tech Lockdown works.

18
00:01:23,360 --> 00:01:25,200
What does this app do and how does it work?

19
00:01:25,200 --> 00:01:36,079
>> The core part of the platform is the content policy which lets you schedule when websites and apps are blocked and you can use categories or keywords to instantly block millions of websites and

20
00:01:36,079 --> 00:01:36,400
apps.

21
00:01:36,400 --> 00:01:40,640
But then once you set that up, you connect to your devices using a VPN connection.

22
00:01:40,640 --> 00:01:44,880
You know, your smartphone or your computer is now using like a filtered internet connection.

23
00:01:44,880 --> 00:01:45,360
>> Cool.

24
00:01:45,360 --> 00:01:48,159
What type of people use Tech Lockdown?

25
00:01:48,159 --> 00:01:49,759
What's like your typical user?

26
00:01:49,759 --> 00:01:58,320
So my typical user as an adult, they're just trying to be more careful with how they use the internet and they might have developed unwanted habits or compulsive behaviors.

27
00:01:58,320 --> 00:02:01,280
The business model is typical SAS subscription.

28
00:02:01,280 --> 00:02:07,040
I have a 14-day free trial which allows people to try things out, set things up, and decide if it's a good fit.

29
00:02:07,040 --> 00:02:13,760
And then from there, they either pay $15 monthtomonth or they pay basically $10 a month if they pay for an annual plan.

30
00:02:13,760 --> 00:02:18,160
Ultimately, I want people to buy an annual plan, but a lot of people give up after like a month.

31
00:02:18,160 --> 00:02:19,920
So, I provide that option.

32
00:02:19,920 --> 00:02:20,160
>> All right.

33
00:02:20,160 --> 00:02:23,360
Well, one of the things that I really think is cool about your story, you had a full-time job,

34
00:02:23,360 --> 00:02:25,040
and this was a side project.

35
00:02:25,040 --> 00:02:27,360
Have you always been building side projects?

36
00:02:27,360 --> 00:02:27,680
>> Yeah.

37
00:02:27,680 --> 00:02:32,000
So, ever since, you know, in college, I was doing side projects, messing around with stuff,

38
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:36,239
even when I had a full-time job, and I just could never shut that side of my brain off.

39
00:02:36,239 --> 00:02:43,360
So, the first failed side project was I made a lead generation platform for freelance developers to help them find clients.

40
00:02:43,360 --> 00:02:52,879
and I just got way too obsessive over like the colors on the website and the logo and the the name of it and I just didn't think about the business model enough or how I would get customers.

41
00:02:52,879 --> 00:02:54,400
So, it just didn't go anywhere.

42
00:02:54,400 --> 00:02:57,360
The next thing I worked on was a landing page builder.

43
00:02:57,360 --> 00:03:03,200
This time I wasn't obsessed, but I didn't really think about how I'd launch it and I burnt myself out before launching it.

44
00:03:03,200 --> 00:03:05,599
I over complicated it and it didn't go anywhere.

45
00:03:05,599 --> 00:03:10,000
And then I ended up co-founding a web agency with a designer and another developer.

46
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:14,879
did that for about 2 and 1/2 years, but it was just really difficult, a hard business to run.

47
00:03:14,879 --> 00:03:17,440
Ultimately, I was glad when we ended that business.

48
00:03:17,440 --> 00:03:17,760
>> Okay.

49
00:03:17,760 --> 00:03:21,599
So, you had a few kind of failed side projects that didn't work out.

50
00:03:21,599 --> 00:03:23,920
How did you come up with the idea for tech lockdown?

51
00:03:23,920 --> 00:03:31,120
>> Well, it ultimately started back in 2020 when work from home became normalized and everyone was just getting way too much internet time.

52
00:03:31,120 --> 00:03:34,640
So, I decided to set up guard rails around my own internet use.

53
00:03:34,640 --> 00:03:36,959
I found out that it's just really hard to do that.

54
00:03:36,959 --> 00:03:42,879
So, I I spent a ton of time researching and kind of putting together my own system that would work well for me.

55
00:03:42,879 --> 00:03:46,959
And then from that, I just distilled that into a a YouTube video and a Reddit post.

56
00:03:46,959 --> 00:03:53,599
And I was shocked by how many people were messaging me and emailing me and asking me to consult and all these things.

57
00:03:53,599 --> 00:03:56,879
But at that point, I actually didn't start monetizing it at all.

58
00:03:56,879 --> 00:03:59,840
Kept creating free content and building my audience.

59
00:03:59,840 --> 00:04:02,319
About a year later is when I actually monetized it.

60
00:04:02,319 --> 00:04:02,560
>> All right.

61
00:04:02,560 --> 00:04:04,640
So, you had built this side project.

62
00:04:04,640 --> 00:04:05,360
It's doing well.

63
00:04:05,360 --> 00:04:08,799
it has paying customers and then something crazy happens.

64
00:04:08,799 --> 00:04:09,680
What happened?

65
00:04:09,680 --> 00:04:14,400
>> Well, I got laid off and I had kind of already planned to leave in September of that year,

66
00:04:14,400 --> 00:04:17,359
but I had to figure out all these things like how do you pay for health insurance?

67
00:04:17,359 --> 00:04:18,560
How expensive is that?

68
00:04:18,560 --> 00:04:24,400
The income from tech lockdown was like $3,000 at that point, which would not have covered my expenses.

69
00:04:24,400 --> 00:04:29,759
My natural instinct was to to go back to this like safety net, which is a W2 income.

70
00:04:29,759 --> 00:04:32,880
But I figured I'm only going to get this opportunity probably once.

71
00:04:32,880 --> 00:04:34,080
Let me give it a good shot.

72
00:04:34,080 --> 00:04:39,040
And at least I know that if I go back and I do an interview somewhere, I bet I could get another job.

73
00:04:39,040 --> 00:04:46,000
I ended up doubling down on Tech Lockdown, and I'm glad I did that because it's grown by 5x uh since I was laid off.

74
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:52,240
>> What do you think was different about Tech Lockdown as a side project compared to your previously failed side projects?

75
00:04:52,240 --> 00:04:56,160
>> Well, I think the first thing is that I didn't start off trying to make a side project.

76
00:04:56,160 --> 00:05:00,320
It was genuinely something that I was passionate about and I was trying to solve a problem.

77
00:05:00,320 --> 00:05:04,320
I also didn't over complicate the logo and the marketing and all that.

78
00:05:04,320 --> 00:05:07,440
I actually didn't have a logo until I had a few hundred customers.

79
00:05:07,440 --> 00:05:12,960
So, I was just laser focused on if I have any free time, it's got to go towards the most meaningful stuff.

80
00:05:12,960 --> 00:05:17,600
It was actually really helpful to have an audience who was really focused on that topic,

81
00:05:17,600 --> 00:05:17,919
too.

82
00:05:17,919 --> 00:05:23,759
So, that when I actually worked on something, I felt like I I wasn't just like throwing something out there into the ether.

83
00:05:23,759 --> 00:05:25,520
I knew that someone would use it eventually.

84
00:05:25,520 --> 00:05:28,880
So, it was it was really motivating compared to what I was doing before.

85
00:05:28,880 --> 00:05:31,759
I know a lot of people watching this right now might have a full-time job.

86
00:05:31,759 --> 00:05:34,400
They're figuring out how do I find the time to build?

87
00:05:34,400 --> 00:05:35,600
What should I work on?

88
00:05:35,600 --> 00:05:37,360
What hours of the day should I work?

89
00:05:37,360 --> 00:05:43,520
Can you break down a little bit more tactically about how you built this business with limited time and energy?

90
00:05:43,520 --> 00:05:51,680
>> I've formed a habit of waking up really early in the morning, prioritizing like development tasks and stuff that just required more focus and attention in the morning.

91
00:05:51,680 --> 00:05:55,919
So, I would do that, you know, between like 5:30 and 8:00, 8:30.

92
00:05:55,919 --> 00:06:04,240
And then if I worked on anything in the evening, it might be more like marketing related because I could do those kinds of tasks without having to be hyperfocused and alert.

93
00:06:04,240 --> 00:06:08,080
And I also stayed really focused on a specific marketing strategy.

94
00:06:08,080 --> 00:06:13,280
If you're juggling a full-time job and you're also trying to do customer acquisition through marketing,

95
00:06:13,280 --> 00:06:18,800
you should pick a channel that is energizing to you and that you can do reliably and that you don't dread doing.

96
00:06:18,800 --> 00:06:23,360
So for me, that was content marketing, but for other people it literally might be knocking on doors,

97
00:06:23,360 --> 00:06:24,880
talking to customers face to face.

98
00:06:24,880 --> 00:06:27,440
It just depends on on your personality.

99
00:06:27,440 --> 00:06:28,080
>> That's awesome.

100
00:06:28,080 --> 00:06:29,280
Thanks for sharing all that.

101
00:06:29,280 --> 00:06:35,520
For anyone watching this right now who has a side project or they're thinking about starting a side project and they have a full-time job,

102
00:06:35,520 --> 00:06:36,960
what would be your advice to them?

103
00:06:36,960 --> 00:06:40,400
>> I'd say make sure that you have a way to get customers.

104
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:45,680
I think the customer acquisition problem is a thing you have to solve before you leave your job.

105
00:06:45,680 --> 00:06:50,000
And you have to have a plan that you can kind of throw gasoline on, right?

106
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:54,319
If I have 40 hours a week to throw at this, I know that there's going to be an extra output.

107
00:06:54,319 --> 00:06:58,720
I wouldn't start a side project just because you hate your job and you just want to work for yourself.

108
00:06:58,720 --> 00:07:01,039
It's really not that glamorous being your own boss.

109
00:07:01,039 --> 00:07:05,199
If you have a problem with your job, maybe just make your full-time job getting a better one.

110
00:07:05,199 --> 00:07:11,680
Start a side project when it's something you're genuinely passionate about, but you would almost work on for free if you couldn't make money with it.

111
00:07:11,680 --> 00:07:18,400
All right, before we finish Ben's story, I want to speak directly to anyone watching this who's stuck in a 9 to5 and thinking,

112
00:07:18,400 --> 00:07:20,080
"I want to build something, too.

113
00:07:20,080 --> 00:07:22,080
I just don't know where to start."

114
00:07:22,080 --> 00:07:26,080
The truth is, there's never been a better time to start a side project.

115
00:07:26,080 --> 00:07:29,360
And thanks to AI, you don't need to spend months learning how to code.

116
00:07:29,360 --> 00:07:31,919
This is why we created Starter Story Build.

117
00:07:31,919 --> 00:07:37,120
It's our accelerator that helps you go from idea to working product in just a couple weeks.

118
