Skip the tutorials and actually launch something real and stay focused and accountable inside a cohort of other builders.

120
00:07:47,599 --> 00:07:49,520
Ben's story is proof.

121
00:07:49,520 --> 00:07:53,599
Side projects can change your life, but you have to start.

122
00:07:53,599 --> 00:07:56,879
And Starter Story Build is the best place to do that.

123
00:07:56,879 --> 00:08:00,800
If you're interested, just click the first link in the description to join.

124
00:08:00,800 --> 00:08:02,160
I hope to see you in there.

125
00:08:02,160 --> 00:08:04,160
Now, let's get back to Ben's story.

126
00:08:04,160 --> 00:08:04,479
All right.

127
00:08:04,479 --> 00:08:06,560
Well, let's take a dive into ideas.

128
00:08:06,560 --> 00:08:08,720
You started a bunch of side project ideas.

129
00:08:08,720 --> 00:08:11,599
A lot of them failed and one was really successful.

130
00:08:11,599 --> 00:08:16,639
What would be your playbook or strategy for finding a good side project idea?

131
00:08:16,639 --> 00:08:24,639
For one thing, I would pick an idea that you can make a very simple version of that's still complete that you can use to validate and bring to market quickly.

132
00:08:24,639 --> 00:08:30,000
If the idea that you're picking is going to take you 2 years to build, there's no simplified version that you can release,

133
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:31,199
I'm not sure that I would do it.

134
00:08:31,199 --> 00:08:37,200
Another thing I would do is start off by building an audience, don't wait to have the product before you build the audience.

135
00:08:37,200 --> 00:08:42,800
And it needs to be an audience that's interested in that topic, not just like your general social media following.

136
00:08:42,800 --> 00:08:47,120
you need to have like a pretty good customer list of pre-qualified people that would use it.

137
00:08:47,120 --> 00:08:53,680
Then you'll you'll have something uh an audience to launch to once you're ready with a simplified version of your product.

138
00:08:53,680 --> 00:09:00,080
If you have limited free time and energy, you need to not dread waking up early in the morning to work on your side project.

139
00:09:00,080 --> 00:09:05,200
It needs to be something you're genuinely passionate and excited about so that at the end of a long workday,

140
00:09:05,200 --> 00:09:08,640
you're not like resentful of this thing that you're working on.

141
00:09:08,640 --> 00:09:10,000
You're excited and ready to go.

142
00:09:10,000 --> 00:09:15,040
and maybe you're even thinking about it during the workday because it's just something you're genuinely into.

143
00:09:15,040 --> 00:09:15,760
>> Okay, great.

144
00:09:15,760 --> 00:09:18,560
Can you break down some of the numbers behind this business?

145
00:09:18,560 --> 00:09:19,360
How big is it?

146
00:09:19,360 --> 00:09:20,720
How much money is it making?

147
00:09:20,720 --> 00:09:29,120
>> In the last 2 years, there have been over 2 million people that have found the site organically either through Google search or or referrals or social channels.

148
00:09:29,120 --> 00:09:34,240
I have 1,300 customers that generate over 15,000 in monthly recurring revenue.

149
00:09:34,240 --> 00:09:38,240
And then I have a mailing list with around 20,000 contacts.

150
00:09:38,240 --> 00:09:38,720
>> All right, cool.

151
00:09:38,720 --> 00:09:40,959
So I mean that's an amazing business that you built.

152
00:09:40,959 --> 00:09:43,760
Let's talk about actually how you grew that business.

153
00:09:43,760 --> 00:09:48,399
What was the growth and marketing strategy to go from zero to 15K MR?

154
00:09:48,399 --> 00:09:53,120
>> So my core strategy was just to write really well researched and helpful content.

155
00:09:53,120 --> 00:09:57,760
I'm going to give it away for free and it made it really easy for people to just share the stuff that I was writing.

156
00:09:57,760 --> 00:10:07,600
I made a a guide on how you can convert an iPhone into a dumb phone cuz I know there's this audience of of people that are just kind of fed up with their smartphone and they're tired of being addicted to it.

157
00:10:07,600 --> 00:10:18,079
So, I basically showed with a a really detailed step-by-step guide how you can make it so that you can only access like a few key apps on your iPhone and like you can't even use Safari or anything like

158
00:10:18,079 --> 00:10:18,480
that.

159
00:10:18,480 --> 00:10:24,959
That article alone, it's one of the top performing guides that I've ever published and it's been read hundreds of thousands of times.

160
00:10:24,959 --> 00:10:32,720
I also developed this a kind of a system or an approach at least that I could use when promoting content or videos on Reddit.

161
00:10:32,720 --> 00:10:36,000
And the thing with Reddit is you can't be overly promotional.

162
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:37,600
So you have to be a little bit more subtle.

163
00:10:37,600 --> 00:10:43,120
So if I made like a YouTube video or I made a guide, I would put like all of the good stuff in that Reddit post.

164
00:10:43,120 --> 00:10:47,360
I would kind of just tack on a reference to like the YouTube video or the guide.

165
00:10:47,360 --> 00:10:49,600
But what I found was more people engaged with it.

166
00:10:49,600 --> 00:10:51,600
So it was more likely to go to the front page.

167
00:10:51,600 --> 00:10:57,519
And then at the same time, there's a lot of people that want to explore the topic further and they figure if you've got some other resource,

168
00:10:57,519 --> 00:10:59,360
you probably are talking about other things.

169
00:10:59,360 --> 00:11:01,839
So I think that's why that that ends up working.

170
00:11:01,839 --> 00:11:02,079
>> Okay.

171
00:11:02,079 --> 00:11:03,600
Well, thank you for sharing those.

172
00:11:03,600 --> 00:11:11,519
Is there a specific strategy or framework that you have when with creating content and what creates successful content?

173
00:11:11,519 --> 00:11:13,760
>> I think a big part of it is authenticity.

174
00:11:13,760 --> 00:11:17,440
A lot of my competitors are kind of these faceless apps or companies.

175
00:11:17,440 --> 00:11:20,640
They look really corporate but maybe don't look so trustworthy.

176
00:11:20,640 --> 00:11:24,000
And especially if you're doing a side project, people don't know who you are.

177
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:25,120
You're not a big company.

178
00:11:25,120 --> 00:11:28,320
And it helps to just put your face on it and own what you're building.

179
00:11:28,320 --> 00:11:32,560
And then when I write about content, I'm not saying we, I'm saying I.

180
00:11:32,560 --> 00:11:36,079
I'm not pretending to be a big company when it's just me working on a project.

181
00:11:36,079 --> 00:11:36,320
>> All right.

182
00:11:36,320 --> 00:11:38,240
Well, let's get into the fun stuff.

183
00:11:38,240 --> 00:11:39,120
Techstack.

184
00:11:39,120 --> 00:11:43,519
What are the tools, languages, frameworks, and apps that you use to run this business?

185
00:11:43,519 --> 00:11:47,360
>> So, a lot of my tech stack decisions were based on time constraints.

186
00:11:47,360 --> 00:11:53,760
So, a lot of my early decisions were things like using Superbase for the for the database and authentication.

187
00:11:53,760 --> 00:12:03,040
And then I would use uh simpler web application frameworks like speltkit which is a little more accessible if you're just a JavaScript developer and you don't go too far into react land.

188
00:12:03,040 --> 00:12:06,800
I was using forcell for hosting even though you could do it cheaper yourself.

189
00:12:06,800 --> 00:12:12,959
Uh $20 a month is well worth it to have the peace of mind and a continuous deployment system.

190
00:12:12,959 --> 00:12:16,320
I think the most important part of my stack was actually the email provider.

191
00:12:16,320 --> 00:12:18,480
I use Mail Gun and Elastic Email.

192
00:12:18,480 --> 00:12:22,560
I think I ended up paying about $150 a month, but I email a lot of people.

193
00:12:22,560 --> 00:12:23,920
I pay for Google Gemini.

194
00:12:23,920 --> 00:12:26,480
I pay for like the light plan for ah refs.

195
00:12:26,480 --> 00:12:28,079
I use Plausible Analytics.

196
00:12:28,079 --> 00:12:31,839
Plausible is just an amazing analytics tool that I I check daily.

197
00:12:31,839 --> 00:12:38,560
It's probably one of the more important optional things that I pay for and a lot of the costs are just on the tech stack side of things.

198
00:12:38,560 --> 00:12:46,880
Infrastructure tends to be really cheap, but all in all, like you should be able to hit a 70% profit margin easily with all the optional stuff added in.

199
00:12:46,880 --> 00:12:47,200
>> All right.

200
00:12:47,200 --> 00:12:51,920
So, one of the last questions I want to ask you is, you know, you built a bunch of side projects.

201
00:12:51,920 --> 00:12:54,720
What have you learned through building these that surprised you?

202
00:12:54,720 --> 00:12:58,000
>> It's actually not that hard to make money with a side project.

203
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:00,560
The hard part is making it into a viable business.

204
00:13:00,560 --> 00:13:05,920
There's a lot of side projects that are basically just selling a dollar for 90 and when they actually go to scale,

205
00:13:05,920 --> 00:13:08,959
it doesn't work out and they can't take it to be a full-time job.

206
00:13:08,959 --> 00:13:11,600
It's less about being really innovative or inventive.

207
00:13:11,600 --> 00:13:20,320
It's just coming up with a smart strategy where your customer acquisition cost is low enough that you can build it into a sustainable business and grow it outside of just yourself.

208
00:13:20,320 --> 00:13:26,480
The last question I want to ask you is if you could stand on Ben's shoulder when you were starting all those side projects,

209
00:13:26,480 --> 00:13:31,360
when you finally started that successful one, what advice would you give to young Ben?

210
00:13:31,360 --> 00:13:37,040
